Oleic Acid Concentration in Italian Olive Oil by Region

Nathaniel Selleck

2021-08-26

Figure 1. Umbrian olives and olive oil in dishes

Olive oil is an important export for Italy, and has substantial benefits to heart health. One indication of both quality and healthiness is the concentration of oleic acid, with higher concentrations being healthier and higher quality. Using the “Olive” dataset from R, I examined oleic acid concentrations by regions and areas within Italy to determine where the best olive oil was produced. First, I created a simple boxplot to visualize the concentrations by area.

Palmitic acid is another major component of olive oil, with some samples having concentrations of up to 20%. This fatty acid is less desireable in olive oil, and has been linked to increased risk of cardiovascular disease. Here I created a scatterplot to show the relationship between concentrations of palmitic acid and oleic acid.

The next step was to test whether there was a relationship between the growing area and the concentration of oleic acid in olive oil. As shown by this ANOVA, there is a statisticially significant effect of growing area on concentration (F=357.87, p=<2.2e-16).

The following two tables summarize the mean oleic acid concentration of samples from three growing regions in Italy, and the mean concentration of samples from eight areas within those regions. Based on these, olive oil from Northern Italy has the highest mean oleic acid concentration. Within that region, the Umbria growing area produces the highest quality olive oil based on mean oleic acid concentration.

If you would like to learn more about Italian olive orchards, or make your own high quality olive oil, you can visit the Fontanaro Organic Olive Oil Estate located in the beautiful Umbria region.
